ire, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","Wales":"Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1226–1266":"1226–1266","1227–Male":"1227–Deceased","1227–Female":"1227–Deceased","1250–1290":"1250–1290","–Male":"Deceased","1201–1264":"1201–1264","1204–1254":"1204–1254","1227":"1227","1226":"1226","1204":"1204","1201":"1201","1266":"1266","about 1249":"about 1249","1254":"1254","1264":"1264","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","Llandewi, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llanddewi, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Glamorganshire, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Leuan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Iefan","meanings":["Later form of   Ieuan ."]},{"name":"Ifan","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]}]},{"name":"Evan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a Welsh name this represents an Anglicized form of  <b>Iefan</b> , a later development of  <b>Ieuan</b>  . As a Scottish name it is a variant of   Euan .  It is now used throughout the English-speaking world."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]},{"name":"Meuric","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Mauricius</i> via Old Welsh <i>Mouric</i>.  See  <b>Maurice</b>   ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Leuan Evan ap Meuric of Ystrad was born in 1226, in Glamorgan, Wales, his father, Sir Meuric ap Leuan, was 25 and his mother, Lady Eva Verch Ythel, was 22. He married Cecilia Clark about 1249, in Llanddewi, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1266, in his hometown, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1226–1266":"1226–1266","1227–Male":"1227–Surnud","1227–Female":"1227–Surnud","1250–1290":"1250–1290","–Male":"Surnud","1201–1264":"1201–1264","1204–1254":"1204–1254","1227":"1227","1226":"1226","1204":"1204","1201":"1201","1266":"1266","about 1249":"umbes 1249","1254":"1254","1264":"1264","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","Llandewi, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llanddewi, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Glamorganshire, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1226–1266":"1226–1266","1227–Male":"1227–Kuollut","1227–Female":"1227–Kuollut","1250–1290":"1250–1290","–Male":"Kuollut","1201–1264":"1201–1264","1204–1254":"1204–1254","1227":"1227","1226":"1226","1204":"1204","1201":"1201","1266":"1266","about 1249":"noin 1249","1254":"1254","1264":"1264","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","Llandewi, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llanddewi, Glamorgan, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Glamorganshire, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","Wales":"Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1226–1266":"1226–1266","1227–Male":"1227–Décédé","1227–Female":"1227–Décédée","1250–1290":"1250–1290","–Male":"Décédé","1201–1264":"1201–1264","1204–1254":"1204–1254","1227":"1227","1226":"1226","1204":"1204","1201":"1201","1266":"1266","about 1249":"environ 1249","1254":"1254","1264":"1264","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","Llandewi, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llanddewi, Glamorgan, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","Glamorganshire, Wales":"Glamorgan, Galles","Wales":"Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Leuan Evan ap Meuric of Ystrad est né en 1226, à Glamorgan, Galles, son père, Sir Meuric ap Leuan, avait 2